  "articleSummary": "The article argues that rigid, fixed-range priority dropdowns in project management tools like Jira inevitably trigger \"priority inflation,\" forcing teams into constant field modifications and unmanageable backlogs. Using the recurring metaphor of a CSS `z-index` war, the author warns against unbounded numeric fields and advocates for dynamic prioritization frameworks like MoSCoW or composite scoring instead. Adopting a pragmatic yet satirical tone, the piece targets engineering managers and technical leads, urging them to treat priority as a fluid metric distinct from severity and to enforce strict backlog hygiene by regularly archiving stale tickets. Ultimately, it frames persistent high-priority tickets as \"engineering theater\" that obscures actual team focus and delivery capacity.",
